feed.title: NASA Image of the Day
feed.description: The latest NASA "Image of the Day" image.

items.title: Cold as (Dry) Ice
items.description: Every winter, a layer of carbon dioxide frost (dry ice) forms on the surface of Mars.

items.title: Space Launch System Rocket at Dawn
items.description: NASA’s Space Launch System (SLS) rocket with the Orion spacecraft aboard is seen at sunrise atop a mobile launcher at Launch Complex 39B, Monday, April 4, 2022.

items.title: Prepping for Wet Dress Rehearsal
items.description: Engineers and technicians are continuing to prepare for the Artemis I wet dress rehearsal test which is slated to begin on April 1 and conclude on April 3.

items.title: Pilot Bob Hines in Training for Crew-4
items.description: NASA astronaut and SpaceX Crew-4 pilot Bob Hines is pictured during a training session inside a mockup of the Crew Dragon vehicle at SpaceX Headquarters.

items.title: Mark Vande Hei and Crew Mates Safely Land
items.description: NASA astronaut Mark Vande Hei, left, and cosmonauts Anton Shkaplerov, center, and Pyotr Dubrov  are seen inside their Soyuz MS-19 spacecraft after landing.

items.title: A Homecoming for Mark Vande Hei
items.description: Astronaut Mark Vande Hei arrived at the International Space Station on April 9, 2021, and will return home March 30, 2022, after spending 355 days in low-Earth orbit.

items.title: Smash-Up: How To Create Rocky Planets
items.description: Major smashups between rocky bodies shaped our solar system. Observations of a similar crash give clues about how frequent these events are around other stars.

items.title: Pioneering Female Aviator Wally Funk Wins 2022 Michael Collins Trophy for Lifetime Achievement
items.description: Wally Funk delivers remarks after accepting the 2022 Michael Collins Trophy for Lifetime Achievement.

items.title: What's New on the Moon ... After 50 Years
items.description: One of the last unopened Apollo-era lunar samples collected during Apollo 17 has been opened under the careful direction of lunar sample processors and curators.

items.title: Contraband Corned Beef and the Gemini III Mission
items.description: Astronaut John Young, the pilot of the Gemini III mission, inspects his helmet in the ready room in preparation for the launch.

items.title: 5,000 Exoplanets and Counting
items.description: A new raft of discoveries marks a scientific high point: More than 5,000 planets are now confirmed to exist beyond our solar system.

items.title: A View to a Nebula
items.description: This colorful image, taken by the Hubble Space Telescope and published in 2018, celebrated the observatory’s 28th anniversary of viewing the heavens.

items.title: Artemis I in Moonlight
items.description: Earth's Moon is seen rising behind NASA’s Space Launch System rocket.

items.title: Artemis I First Rollout
items.description: NASA’s Space Launch Syste rocket with the Orion spacecraft aboard is seen atop a mobile launcher in High Bay 3 of the Vehicle Assembly Building.

items.title: Remembering Visionary Heliophysicist Eugene Parker
items.description: Dr. Eugene N. Parker, visionary of heliophysics and namesake of NASA’s Parker Solar Probe, has passed away. He was 94.

items.title: NASA Astronaut Breaks American Space Record
items.description: In this image from August 2021, NASA astronaut Mark Vande Hei sits and reads while on the International Space Station.

items.title: Who Needs Pi?
items.description: Today is Pi Day!

items.title: Hubble Views an Infant Star’s Outburst
items.description: An energetic outburst from an infant star streaks across this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

items.title: Cygnus Cargo Craft at the Space Station
items.description: This February 2022 image of Northrop Grummans's Cygnus cargo craft is pictured attached to the International Space Station.

items.title: 3.6 Billion Years in Pastel Colors
items.description: The Pilbara in northwestern Australia exposes some of the oldest rocks on Earth, over 3.6 billion years old.

items.title: Engineering NASA’s Return to the Moon
items.description: These engineers developed and tested Space Launch System software that will tell the rocket how to operate for the first 8 minutes of Artemis during launch and ascent.

items.title: Launching to Study Pulsating Aurora
items.description: The LAMP mission hopes to understand an often overlooked kind of aurora, called a pulsating aurora, and to test a theory on what causes them.

items.title: Nancy Grace Roman: First Chief Astronomer
items.description: In this undated image form the 1960s, Nancy Grace Roman sits in her office in NASA Headquarters. Roman was the first chief astronomer for NASA.

items.title: A View of the Red Planet (in Blue)
items.description: NASA's Perseverance Mars rover snapped this view of a hill in Mars' Jezero Crater called "Santa Cruz" on April 29, 2021, the 68th Martian day, or sol, of the mission.

items.title: Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellite-T Soars After Launch
items.description: A United Launch Alliance Atlas V 541 rocket, carrying NOAA's GOES-T, soars upward after lifting off from Space Launch Complex 41 on March 1, 2022.

items.title: Rosemary Dobbins: Illustrating the Space Age
items.description: Rosemary Dobbins was an artist at the Marshall Space Flight Center.

items.title: Victor Glover, Pilot of SpaceX Crew-1
items.description: In this image, Glover celebrated his birthday during his stay on the station.

items.title: Hubble Peers at Peculiar Pair of Galaxies
items.description: This striking image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope showcases Arp 298, a stunning pair of interacting galaxies. Arp 298 – which comprises the two galaxies NGC 7469 and IC 5283 – lies roughly 200 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Pegasus.

items.title: Ted Brown: Artist of the Space Age
items.description: There are few artists in the aerospace industry whose career was as varied or accomplished as Ted Brown.

items.title: Studying Flames in Microgravity
items.description: This image from 2020 shows a flame that was one of many ignited as part of the Flame Design investigation on the space station.

items.title: Melba Roy Mouton – Mathematician
items.description: Melba Roy Mouton (1929-1990) was a mathematician and computer programmer in NASA’s Trajectory and Geodynamics Division.

items.title: Taking a Selfie on the Red Planet
items.description: NASA’s Perseverance Mars rover landed on the Red Planet on Feb. 18, 2021, and took this selfie over a rock nicknamed “Rochette,” on Sept. 10, 2021.

items.title: NASA Tests the F/A-18E
items.description: A top view shows the wing loading test configuration of a F/A-18E from the Naval Air Systems Command in Patuxent River, Maryland.

items.title: Orbiting a Red Dwarf Star
items.description: This artist's concept shows exoplanet Kepler-1649c orbiting around its host red dwarf star.

items.title: Dr. Lyndsey McMillon-Brown: Studying Solar Cells
items.description: Dr. Lyndsey McMillon-Brown at NASA’s Glenn Research Center leads a study of solar cells made from a material called perovskite.

items.title: Hubble Views a Cosmic Interaction
items.description: This image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope feels incredibly three-dimensional for a piece of deep-space imagery. The image shows Arp 282, an interacting galaxy pair composed of the Seyfert galaxy NGC 169 (bottom) and the galaxy IC 1559 (top).

items.title: Voyager's View of Jupiter's Great Red Spot
items.description: ​This view of Jupiter was taken by Voyager 1.

items.title: Mark Vande Hei's Window to the World
items.description: Astronaut Mark Vande Hei peers at the Earth below from inside the seven-windowed cupola, the International Space Station's window to the world.

items.title: Daniel G. Nichols
items.description: Mathematician Daniel G. Nichols, who worked in the Real-Time Program Development Branch, Mission Planning and Analysis Division, is photographed in NASA's Manned Space Center.

items.title: First Rays of an Orbital Sunrise
items.description: Ths January 2022 image shows the first rays of an orbital sunrise as seen from the International Space Station as it orbited above Venezuela.

items.title: ​Dark Mode Activated!
items.description: Divers at the Neutral Buoyancy Laboratory (NBL) in Houston are setting the stage for future moonwalk training by simulating lunar lighting conditions.

items.title: R Aquarii: An Expanse of Light
items.description: This object is, in fact, a pair: a white dwarf star that steadily burns at a relatively cool temperature and a highly variable red giant.

items.title: Climate Scientist Dr. Christian Braneon
items.description: Dr. Christian Braneon, a climate scientist at NASA GISS, presents data visualizations and the state of current satellite missions to Vice President Kamala Harris.

items.title: Lightness of Being: Remembering Space Shuttle Columbia and Her Crew
items.description: ​The bright Sun dissects the airglow above Earth's horizon in this view photographed with a digital still camera from during the STS-107 mission.

items.title: Learning How Ocean Water Melts Glaciers
items.description: To learn how ocean water is melting glaciers, NASA’s Oceans Melting Greenland mission extensively surveyed the coastline of the world’s largest island.

items.title: Remembering Challenger and Her Crew
items.description: In this image taken in 1985, four members of the Challenger STS-51L crew train on the flight deck of the shuttle crew compartment.

items.title: Remembering Apollo 1
items.description: On Jan. 27, 1967, tragedy struck on the launch pad at Cape Kennedy during a preflight test for Apollo 204 (AS-204).

items.title: The Colors of Water
items.description: Much like the sky, rivers are rarely painted one color.

items.title: X-59 Wind Tunnel Testing at NASA Glenn
items.description: This colorized schlieren image is of a small-scale model of NASA’s X-59 Quiet SuperSonic Technology airplane.

items.title: Studying the ‘Lost Habitable’ World of Venus
items.description: NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory is designing mission concepts to survive the planet's extreme temperatures and atmospheric pressure.

items.title: Hubble Sights a Sail of Stars
items.description: The spiral arms of the galaxy NGC 3318 are lazily draped across this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope. This spiral galaxy lies in the constellation Vela and is roughly 115 light-years away from Earth.

items.title: Peering Through a Window to the World
items.description: In this image from Jan. 9, 2022, NASA astronaut Kayla Barron peered out from a window inside the  International Space Station's cupola.

items.title: Remembering Trailblazing Pilot Charles McGee
items.description: Retired U.S. Air Force Honorary Brigadier General Charles McGee, left, spoke with NASA astronaut Alvin Drew in 2020.

items.title: Drilling Holes on the Red Planet
items.description: This image shows the Highfield drill hole, on Vera Rubin Ridge in Gale crater on Mars, made by NASA’s Curiosity rover in its search for rock samples. Just recently, scientists announced that an analysis of rock samples collected by the rover were enriched in carbon 12, a type of carbon that on Earth is associated with biological processes.

items.title: Color Explosion; Beautiful Earth
items.description: This image, captured by the Landsat-8 satellite, shows the view over Western Australia on May 12, 2013.

items.title: Baby Stars in the Orion Constellation
items.description: Scores of baby stars shrouded by dust are revealed in this infrared image of the star-forming region NGC 2174.

items.title: The Milky Way's Supermassive Black Hole Has a Leak
items.description: Our Milky Way's central black hole has a leak.

items.title: Sidney Poitier's Visit to NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory
items.description: Legendary actor and diplomat, Sidney Poitier, visited JPL in 1979.

items.title: Waiting to Unfold
items.description: This image shows the James Webb Space Telescope atop its launch vehicle, but before it was encapsulated in the rocket fairing.

items.title: Hubble Spots Star-Hatching frEGGs!
items.description: This image shows knots of cold, dense interstellar gas where new stars are forming.
